    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-02-09T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-02-09T00:00:00-05:00" n="39"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d39">
                <head>39. Memorandum From the Senior Military Assistant (<persName
                        corresp="#p_HAM_1">Haig</persName>) to the President’s Assistant for
                    National Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                        >Kissinger</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d39fn1">Source:
                        National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, Box 399, Subject Files, Textiles, Vol. I. Secret;
                            <gloss target="#t_Nodis_1">Nodis</gloss>. <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> wrote in the upper right-hand corner of the first
                        page: “Have talked to <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>.
                            <gloss target="#t_HK_1">HK</gloss>”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-02-09">February 9, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>
                        <rs corresp="rec7VZnpkBjTjtzfd" type="topic">Textiles</rs>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>Attached at Tab A are several <rs corresp="recP2zv9bjAjSyYPT" type="topic"
                        >cables</rs> from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_MAH_1">Meyer</persName>
                    containing a pessimistic report on textile negotiations and seeking guidance
                    from <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Alexis Johnson</persName>.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d39fn2">Attached but not printed at Tab A are telegrams 728 and 731
                        from Tokyo, both February 7.</note>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MAH_1">Meyer</persName> reports, inter alia, that</p>
                <p>—tension is building up.<note n="3" xml:id="d39fn3">During a January 27, 9:15
                        a.m., telephone conversation, <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> discussed with <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">U.
                            Alexis Johnson</persName> a conversation that he had just finished with
                        Japanese emissary <persName corresp="#p_WK_1">Kei Wakaizumi</persName>.
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> told <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName> that <persName corresp="#p_SE_1"
                            >Sato</persName> “has the problem of managing a bureaucracy that is
                        unaware of the situation,” to which <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1"
                            >Johnson</persName> replied, “He made a commitment without being able to
                        carry it out.” At the end of the conversation, <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1"
                            >Kissinger</persName> said, “I can see what the President’s position
                        would be though if he had promised something no one knew about and then had
                        to pass it through the government without saying what is going on. And some
                        of it must seem pretty ridiculous to them.” (Telephone conversation between
                            <persName corresp="#p_KHA_1">Kissinger</persName> and <persName
                            corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName>; National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC_1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box
                        1030, President/<gloss target="#t_HAK_1">HAK</gloss> Memcons, Textile
                        Telcons, Sept. 1969–June 1970, 2 of 2)</note>
                </p>
                <p>—in spite of strong Japanese governmental pressure Japanese textilists remain
                    adamantly opposed to voluntary restraints and contend that <persName
                        corresp="#p_TPH_1">Trezise</persName>
                    <rs corresp="recZepXSZhCB1i4N7" type="topic">data</rs> fails to prove
                        injury.<note n="4" xml:id="d39fn4">On January 21, <persName
                            corresp="#p_TPH_1">Trezise</persName> delivered detailed statistical
                        information on the U.S. textile industry and market to the Japanese Embassy.
                        Telegram 10785 to Tokyo, January 23, describes the presentation of the
                        Trezise <rs corresp="recZepXSZhCB1i4N7" type="topic">data</rs>. (Ibid.,
                            <gloss target="#t_RG_1">RG</gloss> 59, Central Files 1970–73, INCO
                        FIBERS 17 US–JAPAN)</note>
                </p>
                <p>—non-textile industries in Japan are backing the textilists.</p>
                <p>—there is a movement to link <rs corresp="rec7VZnpkBjTjtzfd" type="topic"
                        >textiles</rs> with other categories, providing fewer voluntary restraints
                    on <rs corresp="rec7VZnpkBjTjtzfd" type="topic">textiles</rs> but offering
                    accelerated liberalization of items under <rs corresp="recF2jh59vGhjZ2KX"
                        type="topic">quota</rs> restraints.</p>
                <p>—it is likely Japan will ask for more information (for example, proof of injury)
                    or make inadequate counter proposals.</p>
                <p>—the Embassy suggests the following possibilities:</p>
                <quote>
                    <p>—<persName corresp="#p_JUA_1">Johnson</persName> seeing <persName
                            corresp="#p_ST_1">Shimoda</persName>.</p>
                    <p>—Low-key <rs corresp="recCxu7bJCFQ4pEdg" type="topic">contacts</rs>.</p>
                    <pb facs="0153" n="122" xml:id="pg_122"/>
                    <p>—third-party “honest broker.”</p>
                    <p>—tete-à-tete with <persName corresp="#p_MK_1">Miyazawa</persName>.</p>
                </quote>
                <p>In his reply (Tab B) Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_JUA_1"
                        >Johnson</persName> advises the Ambassador to sit tight and wait for the
                    Japanese response.<note n="5" xml:id="d39fn5">Not attached. Telegram 19282 to
                        Tokyo, February 7. (Ibid.)</note>
                </p>
            </div>
